  "text": "To find the total momentum of a population, recognizing both age and region, one needs to reduce the initial fertility rates to replacement level, project the initial population to stationarity, and take the ratio of the ultimate to initial populations. The general population projection matrix to be considered is the 2n by 2n block Leslie matrix, B, which applies to a population with two regions and n age groups and can be written as (6) where a ij represents the rate for births in state 1 to persons age i in state j, b ij represents the rate for births in state 2 to persons age i in state j, and s kij represents the proportion of those age k in state i who survive to be in state j at age k+1 (cf. Keyfitz 1977: Chapter 2; [CITATION_1] . When B represents a population's demographic behavior between times t and t+1, we have the projection relationship",
